Here's a breakdown of where the requested information is typically stored in the database, according to the sources:
•
Date (Transaction Date): This field is found in various transaction tables, including SLPostedCustomerTran, SLPendCustomerTran, SLPendCustomerBatchTran, PLPostedSupplierTran, PLPendSupplierTran, PLPendSupplierBatchTran, CBPostedAccountTran, CBPendAccountTran, NLPostedNominalTran, NLHistoricalNominalTran, NLDeferredNominalTran, NLPendNominalTran, TSTimeRecord, and PCProjectEntry.
•
Posted Date: This specific field name appears in SLPostedCustomerTran and PLPostedSupplierTran. For Nominal Ledger, the NLPostedNominalTran has a TransactionDate and links to SYSAccountingPeriod on SYSAccountingPeriodID.
•
Financial Year: Financial year details are held in the SYSFinancialYear table, which contains fields like FinancialYearStartDate and YearRelativeToCurrentYear. Accounting periods (SYSAccountingPeriod) link to SYSFinancialYear, and module-specific year values (e.g., SLCustomerYearValue, PLSupplierYearValue, NLAccountYearValue) also link to SYSFinancialYear.
•
Account code (Nominal Ledger): The Nominal Account Number is held in the NLAccountNumber table. The primary nominal account details are in NLNominalAccount, which links to NLAccountNumber via NLAccountNumberCostCentre. Posted and pending nominal transactions (NLPostedNominalTran, NLHistoricalNominalTran, NLDeferredNominalTran, NLPendNominalTran) also contain an AccountNumber field, but the document notes that the link to the nominal accounts from some pending transactions is not direct, and the link via URN from other modules is not physical.
•
Name (Nominal Ledger): The NLNominalAccount table contains the AccountName field. The NLAccountNumber table also has a Name field.
•
Cost centre (Nominal Ledger): Cost centre details are in the NLCostCentre table. The NLNominalAccount table links to NLCostCentre via NLAccountNumberCostCentre. Posted and pending nominal transactions contain an AccountCostCentre field, although the physical link is not always present.
•
Department (Nominal Ledger): Department details are in the NLDepartment table. The NLNominalAccount table links to NLDepartment. Posted and pending nominal transactions contain an AccountDepartment field, although the physical link is not always present.
•
Supplier account Name: This is stored in the PLSupplierAccount table as SupplierAccountName. PLSupplierAccount records are linked to posted and pending Purchase Ledger transactions via PLSupplierAccountId and to Purchase Order Processing headers (POPOrderReturn) via SupplierId.
•
Supplier account Number: This is stored in the PLSupplierAccount table as SupplierAccountNumber. It is linked via PLSupplierAccountId as mentioned above.
•
Reference: Various transaction tables have a TransactionReference or Reference field.
•
Narrative: The Narrative field exists in Nominal Ledger posted and pending transaction tables and Project Entry tables. Memo tables (SLTranMemo, PLTranMemo, CBAccountMemo, NLAccountMemo) can store narrative details linked to accounts or transactions.
•
Net value: Transaction tables often contain fields like GoodsValueInBaseCurrency (Sales, Nominal) or PurControlValueInBaseCurrency (Purchase). Bill lines in Project Accounting store the value in BLBillLine.LineValue.
•
User: Usernames or User IDs are recorded in various tables related to transactions, allocations, despatches, and invoices, such as SLPostedCustomerTran.User, PLPostedSupplierTran.User, NLPostedNominalTran.UserName, SLAllocationHeader.UserName, PLAllocationHeader.UserName, SOPDespatchReceipt.UserName, SOPInvoiceCredit.UserName, POPReceiptReturn.UserName, POPInvoiceCreditLine.UserName. TSTimeRecord has UserID, and BOM records note the CreatedByUserName.
•
Source: Project Accounting entries (PCProjectEntry) link to PCProjectEntryDescriptor, which lists the source of the posting (e.g., 'Sales Invoice', 'Purchase Invoice') via the Key and Name fields. Some Nominal pending transaction tables (NLDeferredNominalTran, NLPendNominalTran) have a Source field. Stock movement tables (MovementBalance) and Traceable items (TraceableItem) have fields related to the source area type and reference.
Challenges in Creating a Single Script:
The sources highlight specific challenges when attempting to link information across different modules in a single query:
•
Links from Sales, Purchase, and Cash Book transactions to the Nominal Ledger via the URN are noted as not physical links within the database. This means you cannot directly join, for example, PLPostedSupplierTran to NLPostedNominalTran using a foreign key relationship described in the document to get both the supplier details and the nominal details for a single transaction posting.
•
Project Accounting uses a 'weak' foreign key (PCProjectEntry.SourceEntryID) to link back to source entries (like a POPOrderReturnLine), and its value can be a foreign key to a variety of tables, requiring a join to PCProjectEntryDescriptor to understand the source. Even with this link, you would need to join further back through the source module's tables (e.g., POP) to retrieve all the required fields (like supplier name/number) for a project entry originating from that module.
Due to these database design aspects described in the documentation, providing a single SQL script that can retrieve all your requested fields simultaneously for transactions originating from any module or type (e.g., a Purchase Invoice transaction and a direct Nominal Journal and a Timesheet entry) linked comprehensively is not feasible based solely on the physical links described in the provided sources.
To retrieve this information, you would typically need to query specific transaction tables within each module, or construct more complex queries targeting specific transaction flows (like project entries linking back to their sources) while being mindful of the noted limitations on cross-module linking.
